TERA Resonance Model

Coherence, Confidence, and Stability in Dynamic Systems

Overview

Resonance is often described as oscillation or amplification, but in the TERA framework it is defined more fundamentally as a condition of stable coupling between information, energy, and temporal structure.

Resonance is not the presence of motion, but the absence of required correction.

This document describes resonance as a structural mechanism that explains how systems achieve coherence, maintain stability, and evolve under constraints of energy and information flow.


---

Core Principle

Any dynamic system can be described through three interacting quantities:

Information  — structural organization
Energy  — amplitude of change
Temporal resonance  — frequency and phase

System evolution is governed by:

\Delta S = Gate(I \cdot E \cdot \omega)

Resonance occurs when this interaction produces a stable outcome under the decision gate.


